{
    "title": "Antigua and Barbuda profile - Timeline",
    "link": "https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-18707512",
    "content": [
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "A chronology of key events:",
                    "style": "bold"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1493",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Christopher Columbus visits Antigua and names it after the Church of Santa Maria de la Antigua in Seville, Spain."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "content": "https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/ace/standard/448/cpsprodpb/13A52/production/_126866408_64d2e120-bfde-4ae2-817f-4d9b99edae86.jpg"
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                "Antigua's beaches are a big tourist draw"
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1632",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Antigua colonised by English settlers from St Kitts."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "British rule",
                    "style": "bold"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1667",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- France formally ends its claim to Antigua in accordance with the Treaty of Breda."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1674",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Christopher Codrington, a sugar planter from Barbados, sets up a sugar plantation in Antigua."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1685",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Codrington leases the island of Barbuda from the British crown; African slaves imported to grow first tobacco and then sugarcane on plantations."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1834",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Slaves of Antigua emancipated."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1860",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Barbuda reverts to the British crown."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1871-1956",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Antigua and Barbuda administered together as part of the Leeward Islands federation."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "The Bird era",
                    "style": "bold"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1946",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Vere Bird forms the Antigua Labour Party (ALP)."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1958-62",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Antigua and Barbuda part of the British-sponsored West Indies Federation."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1967",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Antigua and Barbuda become a self-governing state within the British Commonwealth, with Britain retaining control of defence and foreign affairs."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1969",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Barbuda separatist movement comes into being."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1971",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- George Walter replaces Vere Bird as prime minister after the Progressive Labour Movement (PLM) beat the ALP in the general elections."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1972",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Sugar industry closed down."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1976",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- ALP, led by Bird, returns to power after winning the general election."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "Independence",
                    "style": "bold"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1981",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Antigua and Barbuda becomes independent."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "Early 1980s",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Attempts made to replant sugarcane fields, but these are finally abandoned in 1985 because of financial problems."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1983",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Antigua and Barbuda supports the US invasion of Grenada (as it has supported US sanctions against Cuba)."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1990",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Prime Minister Vere Bird's son, Vere Jr, removed from public office in the wake of allegations of gun-running."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1993",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Vere Bird resigns as prime minister and is replaced by his son, Lester."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1994",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Lester Bird's ALP wins the general elections."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1995",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Riots erupt in protest against new taxes; Bird's brother, Ivor, convicted of smuggling cocaine into Antigua and Barbuda; Hurricane Luis hits the islands, claiming 75% of all homes and setting back development by 10 years."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "Allegations of money laundering",
                    "style": "bold"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1998",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- Government closes down six Russian-owned banks accused of money laundering."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1999",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "February - US State Department describes the country as \"one of the most attractive centres in the Caribbean for money launderers\"."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "1999",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "March - Bird's ALP wins another general election; direct hit by Hurricane Jose causes extensive damage."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "content": "https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/ace/standard/464/cpsprodpb/16162/production/_126866409_4485e91e-68ed-4eda-9335-44ae3d2741e2.jpg"
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                "Sir Vivian Richards Stadium, named after Antigua's cricketing great"
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2001",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "Multi-national Financial Action Task Force reports that Antigua is \"fully cooperative\" in the fight against money laundering."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2004",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "March - Lester Bird concedes defeat in general election. Baldwin Spencer, leader of United Progressive Party, is sworn in as prime minister."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2004",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "October - Parliament passes anti-corruption bill, providing for fines and jail terms for errant ministers and officials."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2005",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "April - Personal income tax - scrapped in 1975 - is re-introduced. Ruling party says move is needed to tackle deficit left by former administration."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2007",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "March - World Trade Organisation sides with Antigua in ruling that the US has failed to comply with a ruling to relax its restrictions on offshore, online gambling. Antigua, which has an internet betting industry, filed the case in 2003."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2007",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "December - WTO orders the US to pay compensation to Antigua over its online gambling trade dispute, but far less than the Caribbean nation had been seeking."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2008",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "July - Tourism industry rocked by shooting of British honeymoon couple in holiday cottage."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2009",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "February - Antigua's single biggest private investor, Sir Allen Stanford, is charged with massive investment fraud by the US Securities and Exchange Commission."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "Spencer re-elected",
                    "style": "bold"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2009",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "March - Prime Minister Baldwin Spencer leads the United Progressive Party to victory again in parliamentary elections, albeit with a reduced majority."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "content": "https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/ace/standard/976/cpsprodpb/81FC/production/_126867233_gettyimages-88679053.jpg"
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                "Disgraced financier Allen Stanford"
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2009",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "- June - Antigua dismisses its chief financial regulator, Leroy King, after he is charged with helping Texas billionaire Allen Stanford cover up a fraud scheme."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2009",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "August - Antiguan government says Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez gave it $50m in financial aid after collapse of business empire of its biggest investor, Allen Stanford."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2011",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "July - Two men are found guilty of murdering a honeymooning British couple shot dead in Antigua in July 2008."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2012",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "March - A US court finds financier Allen Stanford guilty of running a $7bn Ponzi scheme through his bank based in Antigua."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2013",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "January - Antigua wins World Trade Organization permission to lift restrictions on US intellectual property, in a possible retaliatory response to US restrictions on the island's online gambling industry."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2013",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "October - Antigua and Barbuda launches scheme allowing foreigners to acquire citizenship with a $250,000 donation or a property investment of at least $400,000."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2014",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "June - Antigua Labour Party (ALP) wins general elections. Gaston Browne becomes premier."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2014",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "September - Disgraced financier Allen Stanford lodges appeal against his conviction and jailing by a US court."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                {
                    "text": "2017",
                    "style": "bold"
                },
                "September - The island of Barbuda is all but flattened by Hurricane Irma. Its residents evacuated before the storm hit."
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
                "End of an era for dynasty"
            ]
        }
    ]
}